# Project: DocBot
# A RAG-based HR document chatbot using Azure OpenAI and LanceDB
# Version: 1.0

## Tech Stack
- Frontend: React 18 + TypeScript 5 + Vite 5 + Tailwind CSS 3
- Backend: Node.js 20 + Express 4 + TypeScript 5
- Vector Store: LanceDB (embedded, no separate server required)
- AI: Azure OpenAI (text-embedding-ada-002 for embeddings, GPT-4o for chat)
- File Handling: Multer (PDF uploads)
- PDF Parsing: pdf-parse
- Testing: Vitest + React Testing Library

## Project Structure
- frontend/ — React app (Vite)
  - src/components/    — UI components, one folder per feature
  - src/services/      — All API calls (never fetch directly in components)
  - src/types/         — Shared TypeScript interfaces
  - src/hooks/         — Custom React hooks
- backend/ — Node.js/Express app
  - src/routes/        — Express route handlers (thin — no business logic)
  - src/services/      — Business logic (RAG pipeline, embeddings, chat)
  - src/middleware/    — Error handling, file upload, validation
  - src/types/         — Shared TypeScript interfaces

## Code Style
- Use TypeScript strict mode everywhere. Never use 'any' type.
- Functional React components only. No class components.
- Named exports only. No default exports.
- Tailwind CSS only for styling. No inline styles. No CSS modules.
- All async functions must use try/catch with typed errors.
- Use const for all declarations unless reassignment is needed.
- No var. No TODO comments in submitted code.

## Architecture Rules
- All API calls from frontend must go through src/services/ — never fetch() directly in components.
- All business logic (RAG pipeline, chunking, embedding, retrieval) lives in backend/src/services/.
- Routes must be thin: validate input → call service → return response. No logic in routes.
- All TypeScript interfaces shared between frontend and backend go in their respective src/types/index.ts.
- LanceDB operations are confined to backend/src/services/vectorStore.ts only.
- Azure OpenAI calls are confined to backend/src/services/aiService.ts only.

## Constraints
- Never use localStorage for storing documents or vectors — all persistence is handled by LanceDB on the backend.
- Never put Azure OpenAI API keys or connection strings in frontend code.
- Never use moment.js — use date-fns instead.
- Never use any CSS framework other than Tailwind.
- Never call Azure OpenAI directly from the frontend — always go through the Express backend.
- Never store raw PDF content in memory beyond the request lifecycle — process and store vectors, then discard.

## When Making Changes
- Always explain what you changed and why before showing code.
- If a change affects the API contract between frontend and backend, explicitly flag it.
- If a change touches the RAG pipeline (chunking, embedding, retrieval), explain the impact on answer quality.
- If you are uncertain about the best approach, say so and offer two options with tradeoffs.
- Show only the changed code sections, not entire files, unless the file is new.
